## Staffing Plan: Seven-Day Coverage, -20% Labor Cost, No New Hires

### Core Mechanism: Restructure Schedules, Not Headcount

**Step 1 — Eliminate Overtime Premium Through Rotation**
Convert to a rotating 5×8 or 4×10 schedule with staggered days off. Weekend shifts become *regular scheduled hours*, not overtime. This alone typically yields 8–12% cost reduction by removing premium pay.

**Step 2 — Tiered Coverage Model**
Not every hour needs full staffing. Define three tiers:
- **Tier 1 (peak hours):** Full team, direct response
- **Tier 2 (off-peak weekdays):** Reduced team, async triage queue
- **Tier 3 (weekends):** 1–2 rotating staff handle only escalations; everything else queued for Monday with SLA

Staff off-peak and weekends lighter — this is where the remaining 8–10% cost reduction comes from.

**Step 3 — Seven-Day Rotation Formula**
For a 10-person team: divide into two groups of 5, rotating so each group covers one weekend per month. Each person works the same number of hours — no one bears disproportionate weekend load.
- Every person works ≤2 weekends/month
- No one works >5 consecutive days

**Step 4 — Improve Response Times via Routing, Not Headcount**
- Build a skills matrix; route by match, not queue position
- Designate a daily "triage owner" whose only job is clearing the queue fast — no project work that day
- This reduces average handle time without adding capacity

**Step 5 — Burnout Prevention (Non-Negotiable Guardrails)**
- Minimum 2 consecutive days off after any weekend shift
- Rotation schedule published 6 weeks in advance — no last-minute swaps forced by management
- Weekend tiers are lighter load by design (see Tier 3 above), not extra burden

---

### Summary of Where the 20% Comes From

| Lever | Est. Savings |
|---|---|
| Eliminate weekend OT premiums (scheduled vs. unplanned) | 8–12% |
| Tiered staffing (reduce off-peak coverage density) | 6–8% |
| Reduced unplanned absence (burnout-driven attrition is costly) | 2–4% |

**Total: ~16–24% depending on current OT exposure**

---

### What to Watch
This plan works only if leadership commits to the tiered SLAs — if weekends must match weekday response times with fewer people, either the cost savings disappear or burnout returns. Set that expectation with stakeholders before rollout.
